tradingRationale: If leader resolves YES, bet follower YES (Ukraine’s official acceptance of a US-backed ceasefire framework is a meaningful prerequisite step that tends to raise the probability of an actual Russia–Ukraine ceasefire occurring later in 2026, even if Russia can still refuse). If leader resolves NO, bet follower NO or reduce/avoid follower YES exposure (failure to reach/accept a framework by Jan 31 materially lowers the odds of achieving an actual ceasefire by end-2026, though alternative paths could still exist).
expectedEdge: The leader market resolves ~11 months earlier and provides a concrete, high-signal diplomatic milestone. When it resolves (especially YES), it should update the conditional probability of an end-2026 ceasefire, but the later market may under-react or update slowly due to ambiguity about whether ‘framework acceptance’ will translate into an actual bilateral ceasefire. This lag creates a leader-follower mispricing opportunity.

market1Question: Ukraine officially agrees to a US backed ceasefire framework by March 31?
market2Question: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by end of 2026?
tradingRationale: If leader resolves YES, bet follower YES (a Ukrainian official agreement to a US-backed ceasefire framework is a concrete diplomatic step that raises the probability of an actual Russia–Ukraine ceasefire occurring by end of 2026, but does not itself guarantee it). If leader resolves NO, lean follower NO / sell follower YES (failure to reach even a Ukrainian agreement to the framework by Mar 31, 2026 is negative information about near-term diplomatic progress and reduces the likelihood of a ceasefire being in place at any point by end of 2026).
expectedEdge: The leader market resolves earlier on a narrower prerequisite (Ukraine agreement) that is informative about the latent probability of a broader later event (an actual ceasefire). When the leader resolves, the follower may adjust more slowly or incompletely because it still depends on additional steps (Russian acceptance, terms, enforcement, durability). This creates an opportunity to trade the follower immediately after leader resolution before the follower fully reprices.

market1Question: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by January 31, 2026?
market2Question: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by end of 2026?
tradingRationale: If leader resolves YES, bet follower YES (a ceasefire occurring by Jan 31, 2026 necessarily implies a ceasefire occurred by end of 2026, under standard 'by [date]' resolution). If leader resolves NO, do not auto-bet follower NO; follower can still resolve YES if a ceasefire happens after Jan 31, 2026 but before 12/31/2026—so any trade should be based on updated conditional probability rather than a mechanical inverse.
expectedEdge: Leader is a strict earlier-deadline subset of the follower event: once the leader goes YES, the follower becomes (nearly) logically locked to YES immediately, but the follower market may lag due to attention/liquidity/friction. The time gap creates a window where the follower can be mispriced relative to the now-revealed information from the leader.

market1Question: US x Venezuela military engagement by January 15, 2026?
market2Question: Will the U.S. invade Venezuela by March 31, 2026?
tradingRationale: If leader resolves YES, bet follower YES (military engagement prior to 1/15 strongly increases the conditional probability of an invasion occurring by 3/31, but does not fully determine it). If leader resolves NO, bet follower NO / sell YES (no engagement by 1/15 makes an invasion by 3/31 materially less likely, though still possible via a sudden escalation later).
expectedEdge: The leader resolves ~75 days earlier and captures a broader, earlier-escalation condition (any US–Venezuela military engagement). That earlier resolution provides timely information about whether a military pathway is underway; traders in the later 'invasion by 3/31' market may be slower to fully reprice the conditional invasion risk immediately after the engagement/no-engagement signal.
